{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492822"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.05,0.18,0.06,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91483"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"526"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old woman develops progressive and massive abdominal distension three days after a laminectomy. She feels nauseated, but has not vomited and does not have any abdominal pain. She has not passed anything per rectum since the laminectomy. On examination, her abdomen is uniformly distended, but soft. Bowel sounds are scant and there is an empty rectum on digital inspection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer serum biochemistry values are normal. An abdominal X-ray is performed (Image). She is treated with gut rest and intravenous fluids. After a further three days there is no change in her clinical condition and her abdomen remains distended, but soft. There is still no bowel action. It is decided to start some pharmacological therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most effective?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lactulose","Erythromycin","Metoclopramide","Alvimopan","Neostigmine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of pseudo-obstruction (also known as Ogilvie\u0027s syndrome) in this case is based on the clinical presentation of massive abdominal distension without pain, occurring after spinal surgery, and the radiographic findings. The abdominal X-ray typically shows marked colonic dilatation, particularly of the right colon and caecum, with preservation of haustral markings. Unlike mechanical obstruction, there is usually gas throughout the colon without a transition point or air-fluid levels. The absence of pain despite significant distension is a key distinguishing feature from mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPseudo-obstruction is a well-recognised, but uncommon event, most often occurring in the elderly population. It has many different precipitating causes and typically occurs after pelvic or spinal surgery and can be a sequela of other orthopaedic surgery. It can also occur after trauma, cardiac events or with electrolyte imbalance. In most instances it will settle of its own accord, with gut rest and intravenous fluid replacement. If there is massive colonic distension, with the caecum measuring more than 10 cm or there is evidence of peritonism, then some form of active intervention is required. Decompression can often be achieved by colonoscopy and placement of a decompression tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn instances where colonoscopy is not thought to be appropriate, pharmacological measures with a cholinesterase inhibitor (\u003Cstrong\u003Eneostigmine\u003C/strong\u003E) or a prokinetic agent may be used. Prokinetics such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E are not as effective as neostigmine. Medical therapies have less risk than mechanical instrumentation, but may be less effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactulose\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated as this may worsen the situation by encouraging bacterial fermentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlvimopan\u003C/strong\u003E (a peripherally acting opioid receptor antagonist) can be effective in the management of post-operative ileus, but its place in the management of pseudo-obstruction has yet to be shown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neostigmine can be effective in the treatment of pseudo-obstruction which is not resolving of its own accord."],"references":["Bernardi MP, Warrier S, Lynch AC, Heriot AG. Acute and chronic pseudo-obstruction: a current update. ANZ J Surg. 2015 Oct;85(10):709-14. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25943300/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91483"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15571"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15571"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2cf4d953-0197-49dd-aa49-75a905dec4ba.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2cf4d953-0197-49dd-aa49-75a905dec4ba.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":341,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevision